This notebook is contains information on the volume of loans issued to legal entities.

Source: Statistical Bulletin / Loans by type of economic activity of the country's national bank. Time period: 2021 and 11 months of 2022.

    1. Total monthly indicators:
  • Dynamics of the volume of loans issued by banks to legal entities in national currency (BYN), US dollars (USD), euro (EUR), Russian rubles (RUB): Total loans issued
  • Total overdue debt on loans issued by banks to legal entities in national and foreign currencies (BYN): Arrears on loans
  • Average interest rates on new loans issued by banks to legal entities in national currency (BYN), US dollars (USD), euro (EUR), Russian rubles (RUB): total
    2. Monthly information on certain types of economic activity:
  • Agriculture, forestry and fisheries
  • Mining industry
  • Manufacturing industry
  • Supply of electricity, gas, steam, hot water and air conditioning
  • Water supply; collection, treatment and disposal of waste, activities for the elimination of pollution
  • Building
  • Wholesale and retail trade; car and motorcycle repair - Transport activities, warehousing, postal and courier activities
  • Temporary accommodation and food services
  • Information and communication
  • Financial and insurance activities
  • Operations with real estate
  • Professional, scientific and technical activities
  • Activities in the field of administrative and support services
  • Public administration
  • Education
  • Health and social services
  • Creativity, sports, entertainment and recreation
  • Provision of other types of services
  • Activities of private households
  • Activities of extraterritorial organizations and bodies
___________________________________________________________________________

Tasks: Analyze the volume of lending to legal entities, interest rates on loans and debts. Find dependencies and anomalies.

def convert(val):
    """
     Converts a string value to a floating point number:
     - removes spaces
     - replaces ',' with '.'
     - converts to floating point number
    """
    if val is np.nan:
        pass
    else:
        new_val = val.replace(' ', '').replace(',', '.')
        return float(new_val)

  • Divide the common table by individual indicators
  • Let's calculate the monthly volume of loans issued, since the data comes with a cumulative total.
In [30]:
'''  Function for slicing our table and calculate the monthly volume for total indicators '''

def cut_table(df, start, indicators_id=None):
    stop = start+12
    if indicators_id == 'total_loans_issued':
        table=df[df.indicators_id == indicators_id] \
                            .dropna(axis = 1, how='all') \
                            .reset_index() \
                            .iloc[:, start:stop]
        table_ = table.shift(1, axis=1) \
                            .fillna(0, limit=2)
        table = table.subtract(table_, axis=1)
        table = table.rename(columns=lambda col: col.replace('january-', ''))
        table.insert(0, 'Years', [2021, 2022])
        return table
    
    elif indicators_id == 'arrears_on_loans' or indicators_id == 'total':
        table=df[df.indicators_id == indicators_id] \
                            .dropna(axis = 1, how='all') \
                            .reset_index() \
                            .iloc[:, start:stop]
        table.insert(0, 'Years', [2021, 2022])
        return table
    
    else:
        table=df \
                            .dropna(axis = 1, how='all') \
                            .reset_index() \
                            .iloc[:, start:stop]
        ser = pd.Series([int()])
        for x in range(len(df)):
            if x%2==0:
                ser[x]=2021
            else:
                ser[x]=2022
        table.insert(0, 'Years', ser)
        table.insert(0, 'Indicators', df['Indicators'])
        table.insert(0, 'indicators_id', df['indicators_id'])
        return table
#     raise 
#         print(f"Indicators_id <{indicators_id}> not available in table")

An interesting situation arises when analyzing lending data by currency:

1. In national currency (BYN), loans issued in 2022 are significantly larger than in 2021. There is a more significant increase in the period July-October 2022.

2. In Russian rubles (RUB), lending was approximately at the same level during 2021. And in March 2022, there was a rapid jump in loans issued by 209%. The maximum value was in April - 64333.9 million. Then the volumes fell sharply. In September 2022, they equaled September 2021 by one month.

3. In US dollars (USD), lending in 2021 from January to September was in the range of 400 - 570, in November there was a peak - 707.3 million. In 2022, in March, the situation changed dramatically. There was a drop in lending to 142.9, which is 207% lower than February of the current year. Then lending was in the range from 107.4 (May) to 252.1 (November).

4. In euros (EUR) in 2021, lending was relatively stable around 600 million. However, there was a fall in February (361.7) and a sharp increase in October (850.6) and December (1038.7). The year 2022 continued with high lending volumes of approximately 860 million. However, in March there was a sharp drop to 85.2, which is 899%! from the previous month - February. From March to November, lending volumes remained steadily low in the region of 80-200 million rubles.

It can be concluded that since March 2022 there has been a sharp change in the lending currency. There was a sharp drop in USD and EUR. However, there was a proportional increase in lending in RUB.

'''
     Function for assembling a new table through the <melt> and <right merge> methods:
        (dfs) - list of dataframe tables;
        (value_names) - list of value column names. The order in the list must match the order (dfs);
        (on_1) - 'str', connection argument, <melt> column name for *id_vars;
        (on_2) - 'str', connection argument 2, <melt> column name for *var_name;
'''

def melt_merge_right(dfs, value_names, on_1, on_2):
    iterator = iter(range(len(value_names)))
    df_out = pd.DataFrame(columns = {on_1, on_2})
    for d in dfs:
        n = next(iterator)
        d = d.rename(columns=lambda col: col.split('_')[-1]).melt(id_vars=on_1, var_name=on_2, value_name=value_names[n])
        df_out = df_out.merge(d, how='right', on=[on_1, on_2])
    return df_out

'''
     Function for substituting labels from floating point numbers:
        (rects) - <ax.patches>;
        (fmt) - default number with 2 decimal points;
'''
# ax = plt.gca() ## Get the current Axes
def autolabel_1(rects, fmt='.2f'):
    # attach some text labels
    for rect in rects:
        height = rect.get_height()
        rect.axes.annotate(f'{{:{fmt}}}'.format(height),
                           xy=(rect.get_x()+rect.get_width()/2., height),
                           xytext=(0, 3), textcoords='offset points',
                           ha='center', va='bottom')

        (rects) - <ax.patches>;
        (fmt) - default number with 2 decimal points;

def autolabel_3(rects, fmt='.2f'):
    # attach some text labels
    for rect in rects:
        height = rect.get_height()
        rect.axes.annotate(f'{{:{fmt}}}%'.format(height),
                           xy=(rect.get_x()+rect.get_width()/2., height),
                           xytext=(0, 3), textcoords='offset points',
                           ha='center', va='bottom')
In [49]:
'''
     Alternative label substitution function:
        (rects) - <ax.patches>;
        (labels) - label list;
        (height_factor) - height adjustment
'''
# ax = plt.gca()
def autolabel_2(rects, labels=None, height_factor=1.01):
    for i, rect in enumerate(rects):
        height = rect.get_height()
        if labels is not None:
            try:
                label = labels[i]
            except (TypeError, KeyError):
                label = ' '
        else:
            label = '%d' % int(height)
        ax.text(rect.get_x() + rect.get_width()/2., height_factor*height,
                '{}'.format(label),
                ha='center', va='bottom')

But this is not the main correlation. Obviously, the increase in interest rates is more a reaction to inflationary expectations.
From the abnormal, one can notice low interest rates in BYN in October (11.6) and November (10.9) 2022 with large high lending.

5 | General conclusions¶

  • Calculate the percentage of loans between years
In [77]:
total.loc['how much in 2021 more than in 2022']=((total.iloc[0] - total.iloc[1])/total.iloc[1]).apply(lambda x: "{:.0%}".format(x))
total.loc['how much in 2022 more than in 2021']=((total.iloc[1] - total.iloc[0])/total.iloc[0]).apply(lambda x: "{:.0%}".format(x))
total.drop('total', axis=1).rename(columns={'EQ': 'TOTAL'})

how much in 2021 more than in 2022 -23% -45% 150% 181% 2%
how much in 2022 more than in 2021 29% 81% -60% -64% -2%
In general, the amount of loans issued to legal entities for 11 months of 2022 is at the level of 12 months of 2021. However, the lending currency has changed a lot.
    1. In 2021, loans reduced to the national currency (BYN) were issued:
  • in USD, 150% more than in 2022;
  • in EUR, 181% more than in 2022
    2. In 2022, loans reduced to the national currency (BYN) were issued:
  • in BYN, 29% more than in 2021;
  • in RUB, 81% more than in 2021;
  • in USD, 60% less than in 2021;
  • in EUR, 64% less than in 2021

3. The lending structure changed dramatically in March-April 2022. The changes are related to the start of a special military operation in Ukraine on 02/24/2022

4. Interest rates on loans were raised to stabilize the financial market and reacted to the shock. However, in the subsequent interest rates on loans went down. However, they did not reach the low values they were in 2021. There were exceptions for BYN since October 2022, when interest rates on loans dropped to 2021 levels

5. Overdue debt reached its maximum in April 2022 and amounted to 6.2% of the total loan. In general, arrears on loans, starting from May 2022, gradually decreased to 1.7%. At the same time, in 2021, overdue debt was in the range of 0.7 - 1.5%

6. By type of activity in 2022, the volume of loans issued was less than in 2021. With the exception of the manufacturing industry, due to which there was an increase in lending. Some areas of the economy have ceased to be credited

7. In the context of currencies, a transition from USD and EUR to RUB is visible. And also the share in BYN was increased. This is especially noticeable in Supply of electricity, gas, steam, hot water and air conditioning, Manufacturing industry and Wholesale and retail trade. Perhaps this is due to a decrease in the volume of trade with European countries, an increase in the supply of goods to the Russian Federation and the transition of payments for energy carriers (gas) to RUB

All the above changes in the structure of lending to legal entities are the consequences of the military operation in Ukraine
